Someone came to fix the floor in my kitchen, so I'm going to pretend I still have a job and work from home while revising Too Hot to Handle.
If I can just open this damned file. (Damn OneDrive.)
*pirate voice* I'm here.
And that's when it starts to really show. Great!
His passive-aggressive way of turning my air purifier all the way up makes me uncomfortable, but it smells like wood shavings, so it's justified even though it's an anti-mask. Plus, I really do need to protect myself, don't I?
I really want to go back to bed, but I can't until he's gone.
The positive thing is that I've finished rereading chapter 4!
Chapter five is long, but full of suspense. Good work.
Doing find-and-replace on … ➡️ ellipsis character, and there are 54 of them in this chapter 😅
But anyway, I'm staying. The most natural conversations are usually choppy, especially when people let their emotions take over.
The artisan is vacuuming, and with a bit of luck, he'll soon be finished.
He left (as far as I can tell) to cut something. So I took a look to see where he was. It's far from over :(
More than 7 pages left in chapter five. It's still my favorite chapter, and it's pretty much finished. Just a few layout changes and minor edits to switch to active voice and improve conciseness. That said, I'd really like a break and a cup of tea, but the guy is still fiddling around in my kitchen.
He just started vacuuming again. I hope that's a good sign.
The artisan is gone!
He said he had done a quote for the entire floor, but the owners were stingy and only paid for the small damaged area near the door. It's much better.
The house is ventilating, and my air purifier is running in the kitchen while I enjoy a cup of tea in the garden!
